header.title: 10 Things You Should Never Say to Teens
header.subtitle: NA
header.postText: Being a parent and bringing up kids the right way, giving them the best you can, being strict just enough and yet winning their love is not an easy task. We all know that words can hurt deeper than a knife, which is why knowing how to communicate with your kids and what not to do is key. Pay attention to these phrases you should never say to your kids or teens to help them and protect them. . . . If your teen is upset about something, whether it's a crush that won't notice them or a fight with their best friend, you shouldn't just tell them that they're okay. This type of response from you will only make things worse.. A study conducted by the University of Notre Dame found that when parents criticize themselves out loud with their children nearby, it can actually have a detrimental effect on their kids' self-esteem.. If you want your child to grow up to be self-sufficient, don't be too hands-on. You can, however, guide them through a problem and help them find the right solution themselves. This way, your child will grow up knowing that everything is in their own hands, instead of naïvely waiting for somebody else to come and make all their problems disappear.. . Music:  . Audionautix - Straighty Baby. https://www.youtube.com/audiolibrary/.... . TIMESTAMPS. #10. 'You're okay.' 0:50. #9. 'I'm so fat!' 1:50. #8. 'Hurry up!' 2:47. #7. 'Don't be sad.' 3:50. #6. 'Let me do it.' 4:50. #5. 'You're so incredible!' 5:52. #4. 'Good job!' 7:10. #3. 'You need to set a good example for your little brother/sister' 8:04. #2. 'Go kiss Grandma.' 9:02. #1. 'I'm so proud of you!' 9:55. . SUMMARY. -Instead of telling your kids it's okay, be their shoulder to cry on, listen to them, and acknowledge their feelings. This way, they won't be afraid to come to you if something bad happens.. -Our parents are our role models as we're growing up, and their behavior sets an example for us. So, for example, when a mother calls herself fat all the time, her daughter subconsciously learns to view her body and appearance the same way.. -Rushing just puts unnecessary pressure on your kid. Whatever you do, just try to keep a positive and playful vibe in the morning, your kid will surely appreciate it.. -If your teen is sad or crying, sit them down and try to help them work through their feelings, that is, if they're comfortable opening up.. -If you tend to jump in too soon, you may undermine your child's independence. They'll develop a habit of always looking to others for answers, and nobody wants that for their kids.. -Inflated praise somehow puts even more pressure on children with low self-esteem as opposed to encouraging them. They start to worry about meeting the high standards you set again, so they're afraid to take on a challenge.. -Asking questions about the details and the work it took to get the result keeps the focus on your kid and makes them explain their choices, both of which help their self-confidence a lot.. -It's better to use phrases, like 'Your brother/sister looks up to you!' or 'You're such a role model for your little brother/sister!'. -Children should never be forced to do anything that makes them uncomfortable, especially when it comes to physical contact.. -Children may start to feel responsible for expressed parental pride, like they need to keep it up because that's the only way that Mom or Dad will feel good or love them.. . I see a lot of teens watching this. Your parents are just flawed humans like anybody else, they don't know all the answers. They aren't perfect and trust that they're doing the best they know how to. If you're smart enough to notice their mistakes, you're already smart enough to make decisions for yourself about what is right and wrong for you and how YOU want to live your life. It's not easy, it really takes emotional strength more than anything, to stand your ground against what your parents might have to say, but YOU CAN DO IT! It's easier the younger you are (and the less of life that you know). You will have to separate yourself mentally and emotionally at some point anyway. So might as well not waste the precious time of your life trying to get your parents to get you and agree with you. Btw, that IS what growing up really means - being free and not depending on your parents approval.

If you need a real role model and guidance and someone to accept you and console you and give you good advice, go to Jesus. He is perfect. Your parents are not.

Early teen here. "Don't ask questions!" This one hurts. It makes us feel like our questions don't matter/are too insignificant. "I'm just looking out for you." NO, this DOESN'T make us feel good or protected. We want to feel independent. When parents say this to us, it makes us feel like little children that need to be watched over. "Because I said so." This ties into "Don't ask questions". We're at the age where we always want to know what's going on. Unless it's particularly sensitive, please tell us. "Stop complaining!" Now, we all complain sometimes. This is perfectly valid when we are specifically trying to complain and aggravate parents. When we're simply voicing our concern, and not rudely? We don't like our concerns brushed off as complaints.

commentThread.commentText: When I asked why I had to do something as a kid I was genuinely curious about why I had to do that thing. Instead I just got the response 'because I said so'. That's not gonna teach kids anything and there probably gonna grow up not doing that thing. Can parents please stop using 'because I said so' as a response and instead explain why it is important to do that task!

Last Saturday, when I was sitting next to my pastor's daughter named Nia (she's like a little sister to me), my pastor and another Churchmate were pressuring her to do the word of the day. It's basically placing a tally mark on the paper when the speaker in church says the word of the day. Nia really wanted to color with me, but her dad forced her to stop coloring and scolded her that she's not tallying even when she was multitasking (coloring and tallying when she heard the word). I felt so bad because they were making her do something that could be a lot of fun and turned it into a chore. After church, she told me, 'Everyone has been so mean to me lately except you'. I know it's important to teach kids to pay attention and developing their listen skills but we really can't force them to listen if they don't want to. I like how the video points out that we shouldn't pressure them to do something they aren't comfortable with.

Don't only compliment/judge your kids based on school stuff! It gives them the idea that their accomplishments are their only value. It can make them overwork to combat bad self-esteem and feel very bad and worthless when they fail or burn out. You should compliment them on their personality and good turns and behaviour as well, on their hobbies and interests, on how they treat their friends, and even on their looks. Of course don't lie or over-do it in any of these - but you should show your kid that you don't see them through just one thing. Because how they think you see them will turn into how they see themselves. If their identity depends on one thing and that thing fails them, they become very vulnerable. And when that happens, they need you more than ever to compliment them on something new.

Bright side, the channel telling you how to do your job one video at a time.

"You are being______, "you always______," "you never______," "You need to be more______," "you need to learn not to be so_______."   Instead, use phrases like, "I feel_______when_______," "I would really like it if_______," "I like it (or don't like it) when______."  

Imagine if your boss said, "you are working too slowly, and it is holding everyone else up."  How would you feel?  How would you respond?  Now imagine if your boss said, "I would like to see you try to improve on your work speed, because I have noticed that some of the others seem to be getting kind of backed up, and I sense that some of them are feeling kind of stressed out."  How would you feel?  How would you respond?

Also, if the teen is a girl, do not ask if she is PMSing or if she's on her period.  This may make her feel like her emotions should be disregarded, because she's probably just hormonal.

Look into it and keep a closer eye on them instead of denying their feelings or emotions, if they tell you they feel like that or have those experiences then they TRUST YOU, they think you'll care or try to help them, don't write it off, laugh at them or tell them to get over it or that they're just sad, or even that it'll pass by eventually. So many people blame video games and other media for their children committing suicide or acts of criminal offences but this is usually because their parent's don't care enough about them, ad say things like this to them. It gives a child the idea and mental image that they're alone and you don't care enough to try helping them, it brings on a sense of hopelessness and fear and that can cause a wide variety of bad actions to happen because of that.. should be "I already had a/did [insert achievement here] when I was your age. You need to step it up and take charge of your life as an adult." idc what specialist say, saying "I'm proud of you!" wont harm a child's emotional health! personally, i never heard it enough while i was a teen and, due to bullying back in middle school and lack of praise (getting more, usually harsh, criticism instead), my self-esteem shot so far down that i'm to the point that hearing the words "I'm proud of you" causes me to be stunned i even received praise. i felt like i could never please my parents no matter what i did, and my grades and performance suffered for it. on the other hand, saying "I did/I had [blank] when I was your age", puts unnecessary pressure on the teen to push themselves when they may not be ready to take on the challenge. your kids arent YOU, so don't force them to keep up w/ what u believe is "normal". things changed since u were a kid/teen, and nowadays some ppl tend to do things at their own pace when theyre good and ready. instead of reprimanding the teen for not doing or achieving something, praise them for what they HAVE accomplished even if it does seem insignificant to u. maybe it's a small deed for u, but for your kid it may feel like a big deal. ignoring their accomplishments and instead shaming them for things theyve yet to accomplish may develop resentment in your teen because he/she may feel u want them to be perfect or follow in their parent(s)'s footsteps when they dont want to, or theyll not bother trying to achieve anything because, what's the point?, they wont get recognition for it unless it's an accomplishment the parent wants/will recognize. i have also gone through this and i'm still going through this even at th e age of 23, and i'll tell u it gets really infuriating when my parents keep pushing and pushing for me to accomplish things when i hardly get recognition for what i do accomplish. ah, speaking of, heres another thing u should never say to a teen or young adult: "Now that you've done [insert achievement here], you should try to aim for [insert higher achievement here]"! both that and the "I already had a/did [insert achievement here] when I was yo ur age. You need to step it up and take charge of your life as an adult." r two of the worst things u can say to a child of any age, especially a teen. stop forcing your standards and agenda on your child and let them live life as they want to

Set the example. If you say something, such as "Its a good thing to be early," follow through with it. Especially when your kid is younger. When your kid is younger, you're pretty much their world. You set their standards later in life.

However if you push it, such as saying "You have to be early!", your kid is more likely to fight you on this. To them, it feels like an order, and kids hate being told what to do, especially when they don't want to.

As for teenagers, the same concept can apply. However it's easier to say it as advice, rather than a simple statement. If the teen doesn't follow through and it ends up hurting them, don't be condescending. No "I told you's" or "I was right."

To a teen, this is a way of saying "You were wrong, and I was right, now get over it." You might not have meant it that way, but that's how most teens are going to take it. However it's not good not to say anything either. It'll make the teen feel like it was an okay thing and a repeat might not be as bad.

Instead, let them know it's alright, mistakes happen. We just gotta learn from them and keep moving.

Another thing. If you want your teen to do something, make it out as a request, not an order.

For example, "Go take out the trash," is an order, and something your teen may fight you on. However, if you say "Can you take out the trash for me?", your teen is less likely to fight you. If they want to finish something, let them, it's usually not that important for the chore to be completed right then. But make sure they don't start anything new, it gives the feeling that if they are doing something, you are okay with them finishing it first, even if it's something like a video game level. Not only that, but it gives the feeling that you respect their choices.

replies.commentText: That is foolish, for sure. If you feel a certain way, you feel that way. It's how you act upon your feelings that can be changed, not the feeling itself.

My dad says that whenever I feel upset about something he feels is "not worth being upset over", and, if anything, it makes the feeling about twice as bad and redirects most of it to him. That may just be me, or it could be common to feel this way; I don't know.

I should also mention that age can help us temper a lot of our immediate feelings. I used to be a wreck when I had to speak in front of a group. Now, as a much older person, if I have something important to say or the group needs to know something, I no longer feel terrified. Maybe nervous, but not nearly as bad as bygone days. Also, the more you learn, your feelings can change. I recently learned a cranky person was having some hard times. I don't get offended by her now.

Jubal Scarbrough That remark invalidates your feeling. You cannot help feeling a certain way at any given time. You can try to learn more about what makes you feel a certain way, but to deny a feeling solves nothing. It's like saying, 'You shouldn't smell this spoiled food.' Well, you do. Now what can be done about it?

I'm calling BS on "Good Job!". My dad grew up drawing amazingly realistic portraits and I developed a similar knack for art as well. My dad gave me a lot of pointers on human anatomy, shadows, etc. Whenever i showed him a drawing, though, he almost never told me "good job" and instead would critique and ask about why i went for certain stylized aspects ("what made you choose the big eyes [for an anime drawing]", "why did you go for that color scheme?", etc.) Maybe it was just his tone, but instead of raising my self esteem, it made me second guess everything i did. It can depend on the child for sure, but i always just wanted to hear a "good/great job!". Maybe instead of jumping right to the details, you can establish "wow! Good job! I like how you did (insert action/detail) to get your result!" Praise, then critique. After establishing that you like the result, then you can work on construction. Jumping straight to "what made you choose this plan of action" can cause your kid to start second guessing instead of having confidence in their plans

As someone who only remembered their parents telling them "I'm proud of you" twice, I can vouch that the occasional "I'm proud of you" is real nice. I feel like this really shouldn't be a problem phrase so long as you establish that you do love them outside of said achievements.

Despite the fact that I don't think my mother ever said those words as far as I remember, I never feel like I have to "earn" her approval because she doesn't treat me differently for achieving something-- or failing to. Meanwhile, my largely-absent workaholic father said "I'm proud of you" twice only after I did certain things and it made me develop an unhealthy relationship with said thing (in this case, grades and writing) that ruined both my enjoyment of said thing AND made me feel even more insecure about how much my father cared about me. Then I snapped out of it, because chasing approval is tiring LOL

The last point I think is missing out on context on what makes the phrase potentially problematic. What should be avoided is using it as a "reward" for certain behavior while withholding affection in all other times, methinks.

I agree & disagree. You can and should tell your child when you're proud of them! But I think along with telling them that you're proud of the behaviors, it helps to reinforce that the child should feel proud of themself when they've accomplished something. That way the sense of pride is internalized and encourages good self-esteem. The feeling will come from within, versus just being dependent on external compliments and judgement. So don't just express your pride, make sure they understand that it is their had work that they too should be proud of. Instead of a blanket statement, say if they earned an A, praise their good study habits and diligence, and let them know that they should feel that pride on their own, not just because it makes mom & dad happy...

replies.commentText: Sarah Hamilfan I absolutely agree. Nice one.
Sarah Hamilfan I have to agree, I used to feel like what I did to receive "Good for you" was something bad. It just sounds sarcastic and to be honest it actually hurts a bit to hear it.
Hanrie Kemp Indeed!

I do agree that I want to feel complimented especially "I'm proud of you" but what he was trying to say was (I am sorry if you feel offended I mean you can have your own opinion)

While it is good to say a compliment especially "I'm proud of you", when the child or teen fails they will expect something like or receive something like "I'm so disappointed at you" so of course some of them try to keep their reputation higher and might get arrogant or cocky though it does depend on how someone takes it.

Reira Charlotte Yeah, I get where they're coming from, I just disagree with them. Of course it's important to not make a kid feel like their prestations are not their own, and it's important to let them know you'll still love them if they make mistakes, but not letting them know you're proud of them is not the solution. And the specific phrase "Good for you" is ABSOLUTELY not the solution.

To me, the solution is telling your kid how proud you are of them when they do something right, while still giving them constructive criticism and helping them improve. Ask them questions about what they're doing, give them feedback, and tell them you're proud of them. When they're not doing well, help them overcome their mistakes and help them prevent it from happening the next time. Do not get mad at them for making the mistake, just help them to get over it. This way, the kid is still in charge of what they do, but they know how you feel about it without not feeling loved or anything like that. They will rather be encouraged to improve and learn.

What do you think is the best way to deal with this problem?

Hey you can figure that out. Good for you. :P

Sarah Hamilfan I absolutely agree! "Good for you" just sounds like they don't care about your achievements. How is that encouraging? Personally, as a child, "I'm proud of you" was one of my favorite phrases to here from my parents. It didn't make me feel pressured in the slightest. It actually made me feel good. It encouraged me to keep up the good work, and reminded me that my parents really care about my achievements. It really encouraged me to know that my actions had a positive impact on them.

Saying that you're proud of your children is a very positive thing. In fact, I remember one time when my grandmother told my mom she was proud of her. My mom started crying. She got so emotional because my grandma had never told her that before. It really meant so much for my mom that her mother was proud of her. And that was happened when I was about 17, so imagine that. I feel lucky that my parents have always been open about telling me when they're proud of me. I can't imagine how bad it must feel that you try your best to make your parents proud of you, but not ever getting it. When growing up, your parents are your greatest role models. They're the most important people in your life, and you really want them to see everything you've achieved, how much you've grown. Getting that recognition is something very important for children.

commentThread.commentText: Here are some things that I think about a lot. That make me feel not so confident about myself. -when my parents compare me to other people -make me try to explain my emotions. Look how absolutely stunning she is!" replies.commentText: I disagree with you on the "kiss your grandma" one. Seriously though, you should NEVER force something on a kid that makes them uncomfortable. For me, simply hugging someone makes me uncomfortable, even when I feel awful. I show affection, but I certainly don't hug or kiss to show that.

﴾*'-Hero Of Time Rachel-'*﴿ I see where you're coming from, I don't like kissing my grandma either, it leaves a big wet slobber 'stamp' on my cheek, I don't even like people (other than my family) putting their arms around me in photos. I will say though, eventually it just becomes a habit, maybe it's because I only see my grandma once a year, I'm bigger on thinking people should show their grandma affection, but I guess the kids shouldn't think of it as being forced, rather doing their Grammy a favor, even then it feels (in my opinion) 'rude-ish' to think of showing your grandma love as something like a chore. Any way if they don't kiss their grandma, I'd hope they give them a hug, at least.

This is just my opinion and I don't really want to start any arguments but I see why a kid wouldn't want to kiss Grammy but as a kid with all of his grandparents 'gone' except one, I think it would be smart to let her know how much you appreciate her.

Yeah, I don't agree with never saying 'I'm proud of you'. Human nature is such that we seek approval. But saying it too much can make it meaningless. I would think a healthy balance of 'good job' 'I'm proud of you' 'great work' would be perfect in a child's life. My oldest is learning how to drive. The first time I took him out I told him that I was impressed on how well he did and that I was proud of him for handling driving with maturity. I don't see anything wrong with that. However, if I tell him 'Im proud of you' every time we go out driving then that's overkill. 

I do not like 'good for you' at all. It sounds sarcastic, like a slap in the face.

It's definitely damaging to a kid to never get the approval from their parents that they need. Daughters whose dad could never tell them that they were proud of them, even on graduation day, or at their wedding, will never be able to replace that need for their father's blessing. My future mother-in-law talks about that sometimes. Everyone is different, and it's definitely important for parents to take their parenting seriously and consider how they treat their kids, even in seemingly unimportant instances. Having a relationship with your kids that allows you to ask them how you make them feel is priceless, and has far-reaching effects on their relationships with peers, their future partner, and future children of their own. 
Parenting is kind of like math homework. If you feel like it's easy, you're probably doing it wrong, and you need to ask for help. 
I'm definitely starting a counseling/therapy fund for my kids when they're born--not a college fund (unless we have tons of money) but money to spend whenever they're struggling and need to understand what's going on by talking to a counselor. I needed that when I was 14, and didn't get it until my 20s. 
I just pray that I will be blessed with a husband with a good job so that I won't have to be a working mother, so that I can spend the quality time getting to know my kids and allowing them to make the mistakes they need to make in order to learn. I hope I never overburden myself with extra projects so that I no longer have time to let my kids be kids. I want to be the best mother that I can. 
My mom does tell me she's proud of me, and it's not exactly as bland as this video states it is. After years of criticism from her and myself, I'm living alone in my own apartment out of state, dating an amazing man, and keeping up my relationship with my parents through texting and calling. There are plenty of things we need to work on, but my therapist and I are tackling them one at a time! Good for me for working a full-time job this summer for the first time in my life. Good for me for working to preserve my future marriage in the way I believe is right. Good for me for saving money where I need to, and spending it where I can't afford to suffer. Good for me for living my own life. Mom gets to tell me she's proud of me when I tell her about everything I'm accomplishing and how much better I'm doing now, and I get to have a healthier relationship with boundaries. Good for me. It's not to make her proud, it's to achieve my best self, for my own sake and the sake of those I love. I'm growing up to be me, and I'm glad I'm not completely shut off from my mom so that she can get to see it, too.
Long rant, but these parenting tips are really good to think about. Talk them over with your kids to see how they feel about it, too!

A lot of the points in the video seem to be "you should say it, but use different / more positive phrasing."  If you're constantly saying "good job" sarcastically to your friends, coworkers or family then using the same phrase when you're being sincere will at best be ambiguous.  Switch up to "hey that's pretty neat!" or "you're getting good at that!" or something.  Its more about context than content in a lot of cases.

Similarly, if you tell them "good job!" for tying their shoes when they're 14.. they're going to take it as sarcastic even if you (for some reason) were being sincere.. just because that's not a "good job" its just something normal people do at that point.  Overusing a phrase can be just as bad as misusing it.  In both cases, the problem is the ambiguity that arises when its not easy to tell whether you're being sincere or not.

As a teenager, I definitely can say this stuff does hurt people in my age group! Especially the "I'm so proud of you" one. "Proud of what, what did I do that made you proud?" and "You don't mean that" are instantly things that go off in my sister and I's heads when we hear that from our parents. (Actually, our parents have said all these things on the Never Say List. They're not bad parents by any means, but I'm reaching that age where they're less Mom and Dad and more like friends, they aren't super good friends by the looks of it and based on how I've felt about it recently. I've also had a similar experience that was extremely painful and still is that's associated with "be the good role model for siblings" thing. I draw to entertain myself, and the way I learn is to imitate what other people have done by adding some of their technique to my style. My mom stumbled across one of m y old school notebooks that I draw like this in and she confronted me and told me to slow down and wait for my sister to catch up- I interpreted this as "stop because you can't be better than her, so don't try to be"). These phrases on the list honestly hurt and I've asked kids at school about how they feel about stuff like those empty responses and they've had the same response as my sister and I did- "they don't care, they're not listening, they're not paying attention, they dont mean it." So, really, DON'T say stuff like this to your teenager. This list is pure honesty and I'm glad our opinions are getting out there. These psychologists know what they're talking about when they say we'll feel a certain way when someone else takes control, when we're put in uncomfortable situations, when our feelings are tossed aside. Raging hormones are enough to drive us crazy, we don't need insecurities added to the mix. So, yeah, don't say the things on the list to your kids and teenagers- it has a negative impact. Take it from a teen.

As for the parent subject, again, I understand they work as hard as they can (my mom gets a teacher's salary as a paraprofessional teacher's assistant in the school Library and my dad was jobless for a year after First National Bank cut off half of their programing department in my city and I've seen how hard the two of them still work to put a roof over their daughters' heads. I mean absolitely no disrespect towards them- they're my heroes). It's just sometimes I feel there's a disconnect between myself and them, and that phrases like the ones seen in the video this comment's connected to, are definitely a great source of confusion. I don't often feel like people are insincere, much less my parents, I just feel like they could elaborate on what they mean by "proud" and stuff like that, like, explain why or what we're doing right so my sister and I, and my high school classes, can keep that in mind when we face something difficult and stressful, because then we can think "at least you're good at ________, they're proud of you for ______. They love you, you can do this." They shouldn't have to protect me if I need to learn a bit on my own to get by. I feel like some conversations can be difficult because of the sides that you pointed out. Like you said, teenagers are in their own little world, for some it might be collapsing around them and others might be only just finding out what the outside works wants from them, and those pressures can be difficult to handle of there isn't a proper emotional support system in place for us. And while some teenagers might seem at a loss for words about what they think about the world, its because the works is crazy and will keep on spinning on its axis like it always does and with all the stuff going on at times, it seems daunting that another day, a harder day, will always keep coming! But adults know that what life throws at you, you have to make something great of it, and to work even when you're scared of it, whether it's to get by, keep your jobs, support a family, etc, you're on it. But that's because you learned all this, or at least, many did, when you were a teenager, too. I think the problem is that sometimes both sides forget that the other one is made up of people who have an opinion that no one can alter. Sometimes no one is right or no one is wrong because there isn't always a right or wrong. This is from the perception of a teenager who knows the world doesn't revolve around her, but the human race lives on it and the world doesn't revolve around the huma n race. No, the world revolves around the sun, what allowed it to live assnd support life. You adults realized that you're the earth and and you revolve around taking care of everyone and using your skills to make and sustain change. That's your sun. Teenagers like me are still reeling from the fact that we don't revolve around ourselves, that without help we can't live, that someone's looking out for us, and we have to take care of ourselves to a certain degree to take care of others. Some of us aren't quite up to that yet. There's that disconnect, and it's found not only in needing to explain a point of praise/consolation to anyone of Gen Z, but also in perception of how the world had always been functioning, because not everybody knows that. That's all I can say for certain for now. I just want everyone to know I'm reading their comments and learning from them, so thanks for the reading material. I'll be sure to tell my author sister all about this and she can include some of your points in a story she just might finish.

Kat Kristar
: I think it's not just about the risk of becoming a target for predators. I think it's also about giving them some freedom - even they are not adult yet, they still should be free to decide whether they do or don't want to kiss their grandparents. I think this simply should be the question of their free decision. :)

I agree with you that forcing a rebellious teen to hug/kiss their grandparents could have the opposite effect.  I think some teens are rebellious because they think mainly of themselves (teenage years can be very self-centered) and discard the thoughts and feelings of others. As an adult/parent, I deeply respect/respected the feelings of my parents and husband's parents. A show of love from the grandchildren means/meant so very much to them. I know this for a fact (three of them have now passed away). Teens need to be taught to think of the feelings of others and especially respect for their grandparents. Time on this earth is short; love is perhaps the most important thing.

Kat Kristar: I can see your point, Kat and I agree with you that love is one of the most important things. Love leads to deep compassion and compassion itself can be expressed by saying kind words, kissing, hugging or helping the others, for example. So yes, a parent should teach his/her kids to sympathise with others. That means we can agree on the final goal of raising children. But on the other hand, this goal should be achieved very sensitively and the way of achieving the goal mustn't be in contradiction with children's freedom because children deserve to be respected too. In other words, I think it's not a good idea to tell your kids: "go to hug your grandpa/grandma" because they could feel they're under pressure. I would honestly prefer to say something which could give them the feeling of freedom instead; something like: "your grandma will be so happy if you hug her or at least tell her goodbye". And I honestly think this method would lead the kids to deeper compassion than just telling them something like "hug your grandpa/grandma". A great advantage of this sensitive method is your kids' approach - if they hug their grandparents they will do it not because they'll have to do it (they mustn't feel they have to - that"s extremely important) but because they'll want to make their grandparents happy. :)
